{
  "texts": [
    "In so-called object ranking, the task is to induce a ranking function r (•) that is able to order any (finite) subset O of an underlying (possibly infinite) class X of objects.",
    "That is, r (•) assumes as input a subset O = {x 1,.",
    ", x m } ⊆ X of objects and returns as output a permutation τ of {1,.",
    "The interpretation of this permutation is that, for objects x i, x j ∈ O, the former is preferred to the latter whenever τ (i) < τ(j).",
    "The objects themselves are typically characterized by a finite set of n features, i.e., in terms of a feature vector (attribute-value representation)"
  ]
}